chargeHist.descr: Use a Computer to Facilitate a Child Sex Crime
Use a Computer to Facilitate a Child Sex Crime

result.execSummary:
The defendant Shawn A. Anderson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Expose Child to Harmful Material, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.11(2)(a).
  • Child Enticement-Recording, a class D felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.07(4).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant was granted 245 days credit for time served.

superMiscConds.notes:
Restitution to be paid on a schedule established by the agent.  There is a restitution hearing to be held at a later date and if need be this amount may be changed. 
**AMENDED** per Judge Wolf on 10/13/15.  NO RESTITUTION ORDERED.

Defendant is ordered to pay the DNA surcharge, and to make arrangements to provide a DNA sample for testing through the Clark County Sheriff Department or if on probation, to the Department of Corrections as is required in all criminal convictions.  Fine and/or costs to be paid on a schedule established by the agent.

Defendant shall attend counseling, treatments, programming, evaluations as deemed appropriate by the agent releasing all records to the agent upon request
Defendant to undergo a sex offender evaluation and follow all recommendations for treatment and aftercare and release all records to the agent.

The defendant shall have no contact with A.H., her parents of any kind, whether direct or indirect, including in person, in writing, by phone, by e-mail or other electronic means, through a third party or in any other way.  Defendant is not to be on or around the residence of the victim or her family or anywhere they may be living or residing.  
Defendant is to have no contact with any minors including his own biological children without agent permission.  
Defendant shall not possess or consume any alcohol, and not go into places that sell alcohol except incidentally such as a grocery store, convenience store or gas station or other such place where alcohol is not sold for consumption on the premises. 
Defendant shall not possess or consume any medication or drug except as may be specifically prescribed by a medical professional for defendant, and then shall be taken only as prescribed.
Defendant is not to be on any social media sites, including gaming applications with chatting capability.
Defendant is not to have or use any electronic devices without agent's permission.

The defendant shall pay Department of Correction fees as directed by the agent.
Defendant is to register as a sex offender and comply with registry requirements and to follow all standard sex offender rules.  
Defendant is to undergo testing for sexually transmitted diseases with 60 days and whenever his agent requests that he do so, releasing information to the victim through his agent.
